<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-446-136  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 446 136.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Week  May 14 1990 v7 n19 p31(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>PhotoMac 1.5 offers users more image-editing control. (productannouncement)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Picarille, Lisa.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Data Translation Inc. (product enhancement).andO;Product:   PhotoMac 1.5 (Computer graphics software) (product enhancement).andO;Topic:     EnhancementsColorDesktop publishing.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>By Lisa PicarilleandM;Aiming to provide an inexpensive solution for color desktop publishing on aMacintosh, Data Translation Inc. has enhanced its image-editing software togive users more control of prepress operations.andM;PhotoMac 1.5 provides improved facilities for editing images, retouchingphotographs and performing color separations, according to Tobin Koch, aspokesman for the Marlboro, Mass., company.andM;The $795 program now gives users the option of working in 8-or 24-bit displaymodes, and boasts enhanced image-editing functions that allow images to berotated and resized, Koch said.andM;Color control has also been improved with a function that displays colorvalues for any area of an image.andP;  In addition, users can now adjust colors inareas where images have been overlapped by using a variety of standard colorpalettes.andM;The program also offers a function called Double Expose, which allowstransparent images or objects to be placed within another image and thenblended in.andM;PhotoMac 1.5's improved color-separation control includes a library of presetimage-output specifications that the user can edit.andM;PhotoMac saves users the expense of sending camera-ready artwork to aproduction house to be stripped.andP;  &quot;We're now saving about $120,000 a year bydoing the color separations with PhotoMac,&quot; said Tom Gordon, manager ofmarketing services for Action Wholesale Service Inc., a Grand Rapids, Mich.,andO;office-supplies distributor.andM;Users can also buy a multiuser version of PhotoMac called PhotoMacEdit thatwill operate across a network.andP;  However, users must purchase a single versionof PhotoMac to work with the $495 PhotoMacEdit packages.andM;Users of the current versions of both PhotoMac and PhotoMacEdit can upgradeto version 1.5 of either program for $30.andM;Data Translation Inc. can be reached at (508) 485-3322.andO;</TEXT></DOC>